g',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(26,2,'2014-08-02 16:00:54','2014-08-02 20:00:54','','Harpa','Harpa, concert hall and conference centre in Reykjavík','inherit','open','open','','harpa','','','2014-08-02 16:00:54','2014-08-02 20:00:54','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/harpa.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(27,2,'2014-08-02 16:22:17','2014-08-02 20:22:17','','lief ericson statue','Andrew picture here with Leifur Eiríksson','inherit','open','open','','andrewlief','','','2014-08-02 16:22:17','2014-08-02 20:22:17','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/andrewlief.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(28,2,'2014-08-02 16:37:50','2014-08-02 20:37:50','','Iceland - canyon walk','Fjaðrárgljúfur, Iceland','inherit','open','open','','img_0417','','','2014-08-02 16:37:50','2014-08-02 20:37:50','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_0417.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(29,2,'2015-02-09 12:00:33','2015-02-09 17:00:33','<a href=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/il_570xN.617392545_2ssn.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-36\" src=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/il_570xN.617392545_2ssn.jpg\" alt=\"A. Herloom MO cutting board. Photo courtesy of Etsy\" width=\"366\" height=\"324\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<address>A. Herloom MO cutting board. Photo courtesy of Etsy</address>Objects. Over the years we accumulate objects and they collect meaning and fill our home. The home is the place we create for ourselves -- it\'s the space that is our reflective, refractive, creative and safe environment filled with pieces from our lives.\r\n\r\nIt just so happens that the special objects in our apt. include a map and a cutting board.\r\n\r\nI was born in New York City but despite my Great Plains name, Dakota is derived from the building on the Upper West Side where John Lennon lived and died, an ode to his spirit. Last summer, AC surprised me with a vintage map of the Dakota territory, dated back to 1886 (Special order from Oslo, Norway. Antique map source: <a href=\"http://www.miklianmaps.com\">Miklian Antiquarian Maps</a>)\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2131.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-35 size-medium\" src=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2131-400x533.jpg\" alt=\"Map of Dakota Territories, 1886\" width=\"400\" height=\"533\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<address>Map of Dakota Territories, 1886</address>A few months ago, shopping in East Hampton, I stumbled on state shaped cutting boards. My first thought was these are fantastic and my second was that Missouri is incredibly well shaped to hold a cheese platter and ordered one in time for Valentine\'s Day from <a href=\"https://www.etsy.com/shop/AHeirloom\">A. Herloom</a>. To make it truly special, the folk at A. Herloom were even able to engrave a star right on his hometown of Republic.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2050.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-31 size-medium\" src=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2050-400x400.jpg\" alt=\"Cheese board in our Brooklyn living room\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<address>Cheeseboard in our Brooklyn living room</address>It\'s great fun having friends fill the living room, slicing Comté off of Missouri under a map of <em>my</em> territories.','What\'s in a name? Or shape?','Objects. Over the years we accumulate objects and they collect meaning and fill our home. The home is the place we create for ourselves -- it\'s the space that is our reflective, refractive, creative and safe environment filled with pieces from our lives. It just so happens that the special objects','publish','open','open','','whats-in-a-name-or-shape','','','2015-02-08 13:39:17','2015-02-08 18:39:17','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/?p=29',0,'post','',0),(30,2,'2014-08-02 16:56:19','2014-08-02 20:56:19','','cheese board','Cheese board in our Brooklyn living room','inherit','open','open','','img_2038','','','2014-08-02 16:56:19','2014-08-02 20:56:19','',29,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2038.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(31,2,'2014-08-02 17:03:29','2014-08-02 21:03:29','','Cheese Board','Cheese board in our Brooklyn living room','inherit','open','open','','img_2050','','','2014-08-02 17:03:29','2014-08-02 21:03:29','',29,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2050.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(34,2,'2014-08-02 17:30:07','2014-08-02 21:30:07','','photo-2','','inherit','open','open','','photo-2-2','','','2014-08-02 17:30:07','2014-08-02 21:30:07','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/photo-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(35,2,'2014-08-03 10:15:16','2014-08-03 14:15:16','','Dakota map','Map of Dakota Territories, 1886','inherit','open','open','','img_2131','','','2014-08-03 10:15:16','2014-08-03 14:15:16','',29,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2131.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(36,2,'2014-08-03 10:22:46','2014-08-03 14:22:46','','MO cutting board','A. Herloom MO cutting board. Photo courtesy of Etsy','inherit','open','open','','il_570xn-617392545_2ssn','','','2014-08-03 10:22:46','2014-08-03 14:22:46','',29,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/il_570xN.617392545_2ssn.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(37,2,'2014-08-03 11:03:57','2014-08-03 15:03:57','','IMG_1769','','inherit','open','open','','img_1769','','','2014-08-03 11:03:57','2014-08-03 15:03:57','',9,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_1769.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(38,2,'2014-08-03 11:33:19','2014-08-03 15:33:19','','IMG_1234','','inherit','open','open','','img_1234','','','2014-08-03 11:33:19','2014-08-03 15:33:19','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_1234.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(39,2,'2014-08-03 12:11:15','2014-08-03 16:11:15','','IMG_0684','','inherit','open','open','','img_0684','','','2014-08-03 12:11:15','2014-08-03 16:11:15','',2,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_0684.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(41,2,'2014-08-03 12:19:32','2014-08-03 16:19:32','','1280px-15','','inherit','open','open','','1280px-15','','','2014-08-03 12:19:32','2014-08-03 16:19:32','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1280px-15.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(42,2,'2014-08-03 12:31:10','2014-08-03 16:31:10','','IMG_1601','','inherit','open','open','','img_1601','','','2014-08-03 12:31:10','2014-08-03 16:31:10','',10,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_1601.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(43,2,'2014-08-03 13:38:32','2014-08-03 17:38:32','I\'m interested in how people live, the textures and materials of a place. I\'m drawn to the intricacies of environments – contemporary trends and histories that have formed local habits. I love detecting all the ways these details create the sensation of a place.\r\n\r\nI named this blog Maidstone | Buttermilk after the places I now call home. Two Dutch settlements turned New York habitats -- New York City born but raised in Amagansett, a village founded in 1680 on the eastern end of Long Island, a hamlet in the town of East Hampton, originally called Maidstone. Buttermilk Channel is the tidal strait in Upper New York Bay that runs along Cobble Hill, where I live today. Sure, there have been a few cities in-between, new languages and addresses along the way, and I plan for a few more to come in my journeys and adventures but Amagansett will always be home and Cobble Hill inspired me to create this blog. Home is part of you, the home you come from, the home you create and the places that you always want to keep with you.\r\n\r\nThis space is dedicated to discovering elements of culture and design along travel adventures in my hometown and around the globe.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1280px-1-3_2.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-45 size-medium\" src=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1280px-1-3_2-400x657.jpg\" alt=\"dakota driving\" width=\"400\" height=\"657\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<address> Dakota, Montauk</address>','About','','publish','open','open','','about','','','2015-03-31 20:55:33','2015-04-01 00:55:33','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/?page_id=43',0,'page','',0),(44,2,'2014-08-03 12:59:10','2014-08-03 16:59:10','','Dakota - About','','inherit','open','open','','img_1422','','','2014-08-03 12:59:10','2014-08-03 16:59:10','',43,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_1422.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(45,2,'2014-08-03 13:37:05','2014-08-03 17:37:05','','dakota driving','','inherit','open','open','','1280px-1-3_2','','','2014-08-03 13:37:05','2014-08-03 17:37:05','',43,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1280px-1-3_2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(47,2,'2014-08-17 15:17:40','2014-08-17 19:17:40','<a href=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2129.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-75\" src=\"http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_2129-1600x1200.jpg\" alt=\"Organically aged crates as bookshelves in Brooklyn living room\" width=\"750\" height=\"563\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<address>Organically aged crates as bookshelves in Brooklyn living room</address>I love the look of vintage crates. And they seem to be everywhere, in farm to table restaurants, bespoke men\'s clothing stores, West Elm, RRL. You name your farm chic, haute bohemian venue of your choice. They have a crate. The first difficulty -- where does one even find these (affordable ones)? At Brooklyn flea markets the rundown boxes go for $17 - $25. I wanted to find new crates that I could age myself. Wine stores, fruit stands -- where do I go? In Missouri for Christmas, I found myself in Walmart looking at a sale on brand new crates. We packed the car with as many as we could fit.\r\n\r\nNow I had my crates. The next step was to find an effective and easy technique to give them the look I wanted. I found a natural vintage-ing process which worked really well. The fresh pine wood in only a matter of hours turned a richly dark with the grains of the wood still visible.\r\n<h4><strong>What You\'ll Need\r\n</strong></h4>\r\nWood/Wood crates\r\n​Black ChaiTea Bags -- <span style=\"color: #000080;\">I used about 12 bags</span>\r\n1 bottle Apple cider vinegar\r\nSteel wool -- <span style=\"color: #000080;\">I added in 3 or 4 and recommend doing this up to 4 days in advance of staining day for an extra dark shade</span>\r\n2 Jars with lids -- <span style=\"color: #000080;\">I picked up 2 plastic gallon tubs with lids at Home Depot</span>\r\nWater\r\nPaint brush &amp; rag -- <span style=\"color: #000080;\">A brush is helpful for getting large sections at once, but you will need the rag to get into all the hard-to-reach spots (read: corners and spaces between the wood) to make sure nothing is missed. I did a second coat on all the crates, I recommend it anyway as I think it strengthened the dark, antique look</span>\r\nPlastic Work Gloves -- <span style=\"color: #000080;\">This is messy but washes off easily. Also, do not do this in a location where you\'re worried about splatter. Because you will definitely splatter.</span>\r\n\r\n​My inventory list varies slightly from the source, from having done a larger sampling of wood crates in one go. Check out the very straightforward step by step list courtesy of <strong><a href=\"http://upcycledtreasures.com/2013/03/make-new-wood-look-old/\">Upcycled Treasures</a></strong>. Happy Staining!','Making New Wooden Crates Look Old and Vintage-y','I love the look of vintage crates. And they seem to be everywhere, in farm to table restaurants, bespoke men\'s clothing stores, West Elm, RRL. You name your farm chic, haute bohemian venue of your choice. They have a crate. The first difficulty -- where does one even find these (affordable ones)? At Brooklyn flea ','publish','open','open','','making-new-wooden-crates-look-old-and-vintage-y','','','2015-02-08 13:44:04','2015-02-08 18:44:04','',0,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/?p=47',0,'post','',0),(48,2,'2014-08-04 20:08:24','2014-08-05 00:08:24','','canoe','Canoe shelving','inherit','open','open','','canoe','','','2014-08-04 20:08:24','2014-08-05 00:08:24','',6,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/canoe.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(50,2,'2014-08-04 20:58:15','2014-08-05 00:58:15','','IMG_0293','Þingvellir, Law rock','inherit','open','open','','img_0293','','','2014-08-04 20:58:15','2014-08-05 00:58:15','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_0293.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(51,2,'2014-08-04 20:58:35','2014-08-05 00:58:35','','IMG_0297','Þingvellir, River near continental drift','inherit','open','open','','img_0297','','','2014-08-04 20:58:35','2014-08-05 00:58:35','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_0297.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(52,2,'2014-08-04 21:06:09','2014-08-05 01:06:09','','geyser','Scenes from Geysir and Strokkur','inherit','open','open','','geyser','','','2014-08-04 21:06:09','2014-08-05 01:06:09','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/geyser.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(53,2,'2014-08-04 21:19:48','2014-08-05 01:19:48','','IMG_0325','Geysir','inherit','open','open','','img_0325','','','2014-08-04 21:19:48','2014-08-05 01:19:48','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/IMG_0325.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(54,2,'2014-08-04 21:23:04','2014-08-05 01:23:04','','wetgeysir','Strukkur shower','inherit','open','open','','wetgeysir','','','2014-08-04 21:23:04','2014-08-05 01:23:04','',13,'http://dakota.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/wetgeysir.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(55,2,'2014-08-04 21:37:14','2014-08-05 01:37:14','','laugarvatn','Photo courtes